thread.title: Quintuplet lambs born to stray sheep in WA
thread.title_full: Quintuplet lambs born to stray sheep in WA

author: Michelle Stanley
title: Quintuplet lambs born to stray sheep in WA
text:
External Link: Quintuplet lambs video tweet 
Although the chances of quintuplet lambs are unknown, landholder and former veterinary nurse Clare Simms described them as "one in a million". 
"There are some documented cases in the UK and New Zealand, but this is quite absolutely rare," she said. 
Ms Simms does not run sheep on her 2 hectare block, but there is a stray mob of sheep that roams the area. 
Over the past two years, community members have taken it upon themselves to catch the stray flock and care for it where appropriate. 
"When this particular ewe was slowing down and straying away from the flock, she was easily caught by a couple of blokes," Ms Simms said. 
"I have a bit of a reputation of being the animal-crazy person, so that's where they brought her." 
Ms Simms said when the ewe arrived, she was not in a good state. 
"I was shocked. I was devastated to look at her because her fleece was all the way down to the ground and it took up the best part of a six by four box trailer," she said. 
"I couldn't see a sheep, I just saw this mass of wool. 
"I got my scissors out and I started chopping, and I was finding pine needles wedged into her skin and prickles that were half way in, and maggots had started to eat around those points." Photo: Ms Simms has named three of the lambs Angus, Spot, and Valentine. (ABC Rural: Michelle Stanley) Lambs just kept coming 
One week later, the ewe began to lamb. Due to its behaviour, Ms Simms was sure the ewe would have twins, but the total number of lambs was unexpected. 
"When the third one came out I thought 'Oh my goodness, triplets! That's just unheard of, very very rare'," she said. 
"And then four, and five, and I just thought 'Here we go, they're just going to keep coming out and not stop!'"
